    "body": "This PR:\r\n- Makes `vim.pack.add()` work inside 'plugin/' directories (like '~/.config/nvim/plugin/mine.lua') without an explicit `load = true`.\r\n- Makes `vim.pack.add()` immediately react to change in source of an existing plugin: delete immediately and install from the new source. This is mostly a small quality of life improvement, but this avoids having to document this use case as \"`vim.pack.del()` + 'change `src` in init.lua' + `:restart`\".\r\n\r\n    *Note*: This is a part of #34771. There is (currently) no \"react to `version` change\" because it might conflict with suggested workflow for reverting plugin (see #36131). Might change in the future, but needs discussions.\r\n- Document currently suggested workflow for reverting a plugin after bad update (related to #36131).",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [],
    "comment_regular_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Regarding documenting a workflow for how to revert from a bad update (to partially address #36131), I realized that merging #36338 behavior of \"install immediately all missing plugins with valid lock data\" can be used there also.\r\n\r\nIf requiring Internet connection for reverting from a bad update is acceptable, then the example workflow might be something like this:\r\n- Restore 'nvim-pack-lock.json' to the working state.\r\n- Manually delete plugin directories that were updated.\r\n- Run `:restart`. Lockfile synchronization step will autoinstall missing plugins at the revision from the lockfile.\r\n\r\nThis is not as clean as a dedicated `vim.pack.restore(lockfile_path)`, but it is definitely less maintenance and code in `vim.pack`.",
